People who smoke have a higher risk of losing teeth.
Smoking damages not only the lungs, but also the teeth, according to a long-term Potsdamer study.
The good news is that if you give up, the risk decreases quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is evidenced by the long-term study of an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutritional Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers had a 2.5- to 3.6-fold higher risk of premature tooth loss.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth failure are caries and inflammation of the gums, emphasizes the DIfE.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors emphasize.
The association between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gum inflammation in smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
People who quit smoking may reduce their risk, but within a short period of time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take more than ten years for the risk to fall back to the level of non-smokers, said first author Thomas Dietrich of the University of Birmingham in England.
One must convince people to become non-smokers, said study leader Heiner Boeing of DIfE: "Smoking shortens the life span."
Not smoking is good for the lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health until old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 are affected by toothlessness, the DIfE said.
Previous studies have already suggested that smoking increases the risk of early tooth failure.
The new long-term study supports the findings.
