Pound rises due to accelerated wage growth in the UK
The pound jumped sharply after data showing a rise in UK wage growth, while the FTSE 100 was boosted by the bidding target SABMiller.
Between May and July, earnings without bonuses in the UK grew by 2.9% compared to the same period last year.
This percentage has been the fastest since 2009 and yielded estimates of the timing of an interest rate increase.
The pound rose by more than 1% against the dollar to $1,5505 and climbed to 0.84% against the euro to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.3730.
The FTSE 100 index closed with an increase of 1.49% to 6,229.21.
SABMiller was the outstanding stock in the market and made a jump of 20% after receiving a takeover offer from rival AB InBev.
A transaction would combine the two largest breweries in the world and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry shares were 0.9% higher, according to encouraging news from rival Richemont luxury goods.
Richemont’s latest sales figures surpass all expectations and also showed that sales in China – a key market for Burberry – are growing again.
Glencore shares rose 5% after the mining giant said it had raised $2.5 billion through a share sale as part of its debt reduction strategy.
The stocks of the packaging and paper company Mondi were the biggest losers on the index, with a decline of 4.3% after Goldman Sachs had set its assessment for the company's rating to "sell".
JD Sports rose 3.1% after the sportswear company reported a pre-tax earnings of 46.6 million for the half-year.
The head of JD Sports says higher wages are endangering expansion.
JD Sports CEO Peter Cowgill says a higher minimum wage for UK workers could mean “more purchasing power in the pockets of potential customers.”
But it is unlikely that this purchasing power will offset the higher labor costs at his company, he says.
The cost could meet JD Sports’ expansion plans, he added, and that could mean there are fewer additional jobs.
