Metcash launches soil consistency campaign to combat Aldi invasion
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA branches from an Aldi outbreak in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground consistency campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
While Aldi is preparing the opening of two sales centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and marketing via social media, as well as through event.
IGA dealers and suppliers jump on board, with brands such as Dunsborough ice cream maker Simmo distributing samples in IGA stores and store owners selling cheap tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29, when the food, alcohol and equipment wholesaler carries out its annual investor strategy day.
Much is at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will seize about five percent of the food market in these two states and remove sales from all existing players, but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in revenue per year and Metcash could lose $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 branches in SA and 30 in WA next year and will achieve sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and grocery business and in the amounts on Metcash’s high fixed-cost basis could cost Metcash about $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley expects Metcash’s sales in the food and grocery business to fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, and reduce its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, Lead Fund Manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr. Douglass’ comments.
But it is assumed that a Metcash board member contacted Mr. Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenue from Metcash’s food and grocery trade, which supplies approximately 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operational debt reduction while simultaneously pressuring revenue and margins.
However, the wholesaler is resisting and investing more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths for hundreds of products each week, and to improve IGA retailers’ ability to improve their stores by growing fresh foods faster and delivering a better selection of private label foods.
Metcash CEO Ian Morrice says that the price adjustments and store renovation programs will increase to Elan and hopes that the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is supported by the President of the Australian Tennis Association Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves more praise than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damages" in the recent storm around his friend Nick Kyrgios and, according to Australian tennis federation president Steve Healy, deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behavior.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, who is repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks", came to the spotlight through Kyrgios' infamous confrontation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated by the referee twice, with Harrison exclaiming, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten the child."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis bat after a spasm defeated a potential U.S. Open victory by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was firmly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second singles place behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-finals against Great Britain.
"One thing I'm pretty much jealous about is the fact that in my opinion Thanasi was a bit involved in the dispute," Healy said.
He broke a bat when he lost to a cramps at the U.S. Open, but he’s not the first player to break a bat out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he’s not proud of it.
But, really, he behaved extremely well in the US Open, even under the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he’s been treated a little too harshly.
He is a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he has never had a problem with the other players, he is respected in the dressing area, he trains hard, he is in good shape, he is a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be paid according to his own merit.
Healy also supported the decision not to take Kyrgios into account in the important pre-decision that begins on Friday, and he describes the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assures the man from Canberra to return to the team as a long-term solid component."
“First, we want the team to be fully focused on the competition and not on all the controversies around [Kyrgios],” Healy said.
And I believe that Nick has managed the rise very quickly, which people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He rises in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions beyond the one time I can only make him understand.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares state of emergency, closes border, holds back refugees
Hungary declared a state of emergency and blocked the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, detaining all those who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man’s land and Serbian officials reacted with indignation.
The people who had fled violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations increased.
As a police helicopter hovered over them, the migrants chanted “Open the border!” and shouted insults to the Hungarian police.
Some rejected food and water in protest.
Serbia's foreign minister said it was "unacceptable" that migrants would be sent back from Hungary as more and more arrived from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
Talks with Brussels and other countries must take place in the coming days," said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc failed to agree on a common immigration policy at a disputed meeting in Brussels.
The ministers, however, agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in overwhelmed Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that the EU states would take on another 120,000 refugees, including some from Un.
Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria on Tuesday called for a special EU summit to discuss the continent’s immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not set its hopes on an immediate action by Brussels or its neighbours.
The state of emergency declared on Tuesday in two southern regions gave authorities more powers to cope with the crisis, allowing them to block roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said his country was also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country after it ended a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D’Agata reported that even prisoners were employed in the race to create the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a significant bottleneck and entry point for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
Prime Minister Viktor Orban, however, has insisted that most of the incoming are economic refugees seeking a better life, not war refugees entitled to protection – a view that is strongly opposed to other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-meter (13 ft) high fence that the government had built along the southern border with Serbia a crime. These laws also impose higher prison sentences for convicted human traffickers.
"Due to the situation created by the mass migration, the Hungarian government declares the state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: illegal border crossing is a crime.
The parliament still has to approve the military’s deployment, which is expected next week, but reporters from the Associated Press have seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, Orban's national security adviser, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train wagon with barbed wire arrived to close the borders.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process people’s data and pushed a crowd to sneak into it.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway link between Serbia and Hungary, saying they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
2016 Election: Hillary Clinton's lead halved over Bernie Sanders in national poll
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a two-figure lead in the Democratic race for nominations at the national level, but Senator Bernie Sanders wins against her on the ground.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the pre-election (58 percent before), while Sanders is in second place, with 27 percent (an increase of 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether he is running for president, will receive support from 15 percent of the Democratic primary voters.
More than five months before the start of the pre-election, most Democratic voters say it is too early to say that their opinion is firm on which candidates they will support.
But Clinton’s supporters are more consistent in their election than those of the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups, while Sanders made some gains.
Clinton holds a big lead among women and moderates, but these leads have diminished.
Their support among the men has declined significantly, and Sanders is only 5 points behind here.
Clinton’s advantage over democratic voters under the age of 50 has evaporated, and she and Sanders are now at the same level.
Clinton, however, still has a big lead among older voters.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a two-digit lead in the Liberals, but Sanders now has a five-point lead in this group.
About half of Democratic voters across the country say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if she were nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations, and another 15 percent would only support her because she is the candidate.
Six percent would not support it.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton’s current supporters are especially enthusiastic about her.
The views are more mixed with those who don’t currently support Clinton – only about a quarter would enthusiastically support them.
While 48 percent of Democratic voters say they support Clinton enthusiastically, fewer Republican voters say this about their top candidate Donald Trump (35 percent).
When Clinton’s supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16 percent), followed by the view that it’s time for a woman to become president (13 percent) and that she is the best candidate for the job (10 percent).
Clinton’s supporters also mention her connection to Bill Clinton (9%).
Consent to deal with the problems and eligibility are also cited.
As the vice president throws a potential for the presidential office into the balance sheet, 57 percent of Democratic voters want to see him in the race – though a third believe he shouldn’t.
When Democratic voters are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the forefront.
Of Clinton’s supporters, more than half say Biden’s second choice would be far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton’s lead over Sanders increases from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as the candidate with the best chance of winning the election; however, that figure has fallen from 78 percent last month.
Biden is by far second in this measurement, but the percentage he considers the "most selectable" has risen.
Yet, when asked what is more important to a candidate, Democratic voters raise questions about eligibility.
Like last month, not a single Democratic candidate or potential candidate for these voters stands out as unacceptable.
Democratic candidates, or potential candidates, deliver good results on some important features among voters in their party’s pre-elections.
Majorities view Clinton, Sanders and Biden as honest and trustworthy and equipped with strong leadership qualities.
Biden cuts off the three candidates best in honesty, while Clinton’s strength is in the lead.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters do not believe that Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say that about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent have no opinion of him.
Democratic voters in the presidential election generally also see Clinton, Sanders and Biden ideologically in line with their views.
In all these measurements, about a quarter of the Democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
As questions about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and a server continue to be asked during her tenure as secretary of state, most Democratic voters in the pre-election are satisfied with her statement on the matter and say it has not affected their opinions overall.
But it’s a different story in the American public as a whole.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third are satisfied.
Public opinion on this was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said that the email controversy had no effect on their general opinions of Clinton, although 36 percent said their opinion of her had worsened.
It’s mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views on Clinton have gotten worse.
Although Clinton is considered honest and trustworthy by her party’s voters, this remains a problem for her among registered voters overall: only 32 percent see it as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month and 15 points less than since May.
62% of voters do not believe they are an honest and trustworthy person.
At the same time, 55 percent of voters across the country also view Trump as dishonest and untrustworthy.
However, Clinton and Trump get good grades in leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson, and Bush are best cut off in honesty.
A majority looks more like Sanders than honest, but like Carson, many have no opinion of him.
The error rate for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the primary elections is 6 percentage points.
