Five Brotherhood Members Charged with the Death of a Baruch College Newborn
Nearly two years after a student died during a harassing ritual of a student union in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges are filed against five people.
Members of the New York Baruch College Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood brutally attacked Chun "Michael" Deng during an introduction ritual in September 2013 and delayed his transport to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he was loaded with eyes closed with a 30-pound backpack full of sand, and repeatedly attacked while trying to reach a target via a frozen field.
Mr. Deng finally complained of a headache, then he fell unconscious.
Members of the Pi-Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call 911 after Deng became powerless and allegedly waited an hour before taking him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had time to change Deng’s clothes, google his symptoms, and contact Andy Meng, the fraternity’s national president, to seek advice, police chief Chris Wagner said at a press conference.
"At this point, members began hiding utensils and basically put the well-being of the fraternity above that of Michael Deng," said police chief Wagner.
He could not be revived, and he died the next morning from his injuries.
After an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly inflicted with blunt force injuries to the head, torso and thighs.
"Too many families have been destroyed by the harassment of the Brotherhood. At least one student has died from the harassment every year since 1970," Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng's family, said in a statement.
Brotherhoods and their members need to be held accountable, and this step by authorities is very important.
A County Grand Jury of Monroe recommended an indictment for third-degree murder for the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the Brotherhood, including Mr. Meng, are also charged with harassing attacks and the formation of a criminal association.
"We not only want to hold those involved accountable, but if there is an organization that has - officially or unofficially - sanctioned this, we will also hold them accountable," Wagner said at a news conference on Tuesday.
The Baruch College has banned the fraternity, and the national fraternity has revoked its membership in the local group.
This will happen when the Fed raises interest rates.
An interest rate hike is coming, and the rise will fluctuate, yields for bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into recession.
We know that.
What we do not know is how long this will take and how long it will last.
In particular, history offers little guidance for the economy on how to proceed.
A recession occurred within just 11 months of the first interest rate increase and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
That’s why U.S. central bank officials have so strongly stressed that investors should not focus on when they start raising interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that the whole excitement due to an interest rate hike may have been exaggerated.
“The Fed’s first increase since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the ‘cheap money’ era,” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal levels, but still at too low a level to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here’s a look at how some sectors of the economy might react based on historical trends:
As the market has seen over the past month, anticipating interest rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase arrives, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency for asset returns to be staggered 12 to 24 months after the first increase, perhaps reflecting the delay in monetary policy again,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
More specifically, the market has been in the upward trend in the past 35 years - about 14 percent - on the way to interest rate increase, rather flat in the 250 days after (average profit of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return at the last six years, with a bar rate of 14 percent in the last six years, the rate of change in the past four years, the rate of change in the past four years.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on the shares tends to occur later in the increase cycle and the return starts to decrease.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate hikes often promote them.
In the current case, the Fed is facing some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
What is particularly noteworthy here is that the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point at a rate hike by the Fed.
According to Deutsche Bank, among the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes in such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky and raise the question of "whether it's different this time," Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been gearing up for a Fed interest rate hike all year, and all eyes were on this week’s meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee, which ends Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only indicates a 25 percent probability.
“In our study, all increase cycles from 1950 to today took place in a super cycle with increasing momentum at GDP and pre-recession heights eclipsed very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
In contrast, this is clearly a slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate increase, and the pattern is quite similar to that of the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic price.
In the case of bonds, returns appear to change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
The strategists of Charles Schwab believe that the rise in interest rates will bring returns closer together between longer and shorter bonds and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-yield bonds often bring better returns in such a climate, although “we are still cautious about expecting higher returns,” said Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adjusted to Fed strategy expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have expanded, and volatility has increased – all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
On the whole, companies that do most of their business in the U.S. will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debts will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market as well as financing their debts.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks tend to respond extremely positively three months after an initial interest rate hike,” Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Firms with a strong balance sheet have surpassed firms with a weak balance sheet by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their shares also exceeded their low quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure equity games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see profits from higher returns, even if experts disagree on how quickly this will happen.
