At their most anticipated meeting of the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras-Mahagoni table to decide if it’s time to raise the lead rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Threateningly above them at one end of the decorated, two-story meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The card is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation’s economic interests above all other things.
The central bank has a double mandate from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed leaders have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X-Factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict it. It will be announced on Thursday whether the US economy is ready to start off from the unprecedented stimulus by the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Although most of the economy’s data shows it’s growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials into aggravating this volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds — even if it’s only a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing they’re seeing,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is justification enough to continue to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself insures the financial market.
About half of economists surveyed by Bloomberg recently predicted an interest rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect a wait on the Fed, with a key indicator indicating only a 30% chance of an increase.
This indicates a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate, unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that another rise is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped by 228.89 points or 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The move was triggered by expectations that Fed policy will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed would raise rates at this point,” he said.
If she does, "should she go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so that they don't panic."
Other experts argued that an interest rate hike would calm the financial markets because it would eliminate the uncertainty about when the Fed would trade.
A month ago, the Fed seemed well on its way to raising the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the recovery in the United States.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress would be needed, she expected an increase in the rate this year.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed sees as full employment.
Increases in wages have shown signs of recovery.
And while inflation was consistently below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, Fed officials said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher interest rates and needs them because of the stresses in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world tightened at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell more than 16 percent below its peak in May when investors feared a slowdown in China’s economy would stifle global growth.
The market has recovered slightly this month, with the Dow now nearly 10% below its May high.
For the Fed representatives, market turbulence affects the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news of the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks, they would have taken the reins in this session,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the U.S. Central Bank.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there's almost no reliable data describing developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not one of the main concerns of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
The central bank’s influence has been enormous in recent years.
The mere remark by then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “shrink” its monetary expansion sparked confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global asset management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, noted this month that “the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that are apparently unrelated to the economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, which advocates an interest rate hike, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia prompted the Fed to lower its lead interest rate by 0.75% in three sessions “despite limited recognizable impacts on U.S. growth,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed these cuts.
The Fed should only put aspects of financial stability first during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
The recent turmoil does not come close to this level, he said.
“She certainly doesn’t want to get into a situation where she’s afraid of an interest rate hike because markets are getting upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don’t think it should be ahead of time.
