Fourfold increase in children’s use of hand sanitizers in the last 4 years
U.S. poison control centers report a nearly 400-percent increase in the number of children under the age of twelve who swallow heavily alcoholic hand sanitizers, according to the Georgia Poison Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Center, cases of hand sanitizer intake in children under 12 years of age reportedly rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children are increasingly coming to these products, and unfortunately, a percentage of them end up going to the emergency room," Lopez told CNN.
He said some children deliberately drink disinfectants, while some do so to impress their friends or because of a test of courage on social media.
Videos on YouTube show how teens drink disinfectants only because of a cheap experience.
Teens have allegedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to get a harder drink.
Younger children can be attracted to attractive fragrances of disinfectants.
“A child doesn’t think this is bad for him,” Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand disinfectants) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with strawberry, grape and orange scents that are very appealing to children.
Hand sanitizers contain between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, few sprays can lead to alcohol poisoning.
“It’s highly concentrated alcohol,” Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Poison Emergency Center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
So, you wouldn’t leave a sip of whiskey around, but people leave these hand sanitizers within reach of children, and if children get it, then it’s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four sprays of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol concentration was 179, twice the threshold that is legally considered drunk in an adult, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah lamented her words and was unable to go when she arrived in the emergency room.
Doctors monitored them overnight in a separate children's hospital for signs of brain trauma as the girl had fallen through the alcohol and bumped her head, Ritchey said.
"That was very frightening," Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been deadly for my child.
Lopez has recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic products or disinfectants and store hand sanitizers outside the child’s reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants were associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand sanitizers that contained a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect the product contained methanol, a deadly solution rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-grade students in New York State planned to poison their “bad” teacher by exposing antibacterial products around the classroom, according to a police report.
The teacher is highly allergic to hand sanitizers and banished her from her room.
The police considered the failed plan to be "talk" and referred disciplinary measures to the school authority.
