Robotic cars: government wants to be a pioneer for Germany
According to the Federal Government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the change of the car.
On Wednesday, the Federal Cabinet adopted a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which provides for investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure, among other things.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the edge of the Automesse IAA of a "new mobility era".
Automated and connected driving will increase road safety and reduce traffic congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his G7 counterparts, who also meet with representatives of the industry at the IAA.
The strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasizes, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid transition to digital radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being created on the highway 9 in Bavaria.
In order for the driver to be "no additional liability risks" the federal government wants to "review the legal framework conditions and, where necessary, adapt to the new developments".
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the maximum permissible speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres per hour.
The federal government also wants to advocate for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
With automated driving, the car increasingly takes over the lead, the driver becomes more and more the passenger.
The technology is primarily based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economy, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
However, driverless vehicles on public roads are “only to be expected far beyond 2020.”
The value added in the field of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the location in Germany is estimated by the authors of the study to be around 8.4 billion euros for 2025.
"Digital networking of cars can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD traffic politician Sören Bartol.
However, the question of liability in the event of accidents and the security of personal data of drivers must be clearly clarified.
However, Germans still see self-driving cars skeptical – much more than French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the testing organisation Dekra, presented on Wednesday at the AA, concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent do not expect it until 20 years, 31 percent do not believe it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, while in the US, 33 percent expect autonomous cars.
After all, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely completely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to give up control throughout the ride on all roads.
On the highway, this could be imagined in the flowing traffic at least 15 percent, in the congestion 45 percent.
One in four people would not leave the car under any circumstances.
