Xi urges to open the economy wider to the world
The economy needs to open up more broadly to the outside world to drive growth, President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday of a group tasked with leading the reform.
"China should be committed to attracting foreign investment and know-how and improving business start-up strategies," he said in a speech at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group to deepen a comprehensive reform.
Fostering new start-ups and advancing reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list on regulating market access, relaxing border control policies, promoting state-owned enterprises (SOEs), incorporating private capital, and overhauling the resident reporting system.
After the statement, a negative list is created that identifies sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually tested and improved by testing programs.
The initiative is important because it assigns a greater role to the market in allocating resources, ensures a rule of law business environment and makes the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls over the powers delegated to companies and ensure that companies decide how to conduct their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of an offer to open state-controlled sectors, additional areas for private investment will be opened.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide better services to them," the statement said.
In addition, it will make it easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the "Green Card" by optimizing the requirements and facilitating the application process.
The right of lawyers to guarantee the exercise of their duties and to employ professional judges and public prosecutors was also discussed at a meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and key leaders such as Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, as reported in a statement released after the meeting.
EU aims to double mercury limit in predatory fishery
The European Commission aims to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish, thereby giving consumers a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, sharply criticised the plans: "The risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are being passed on with full force to pregnant women and toddlers," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limit values of the neurotoxicity for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, should be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily charged with mercury that about 50 percent of the catches are not allowed to be sold on the basis of the limit values still in force.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unselling.
In return for this relaxation, the EU wants to tighten the limit values for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch called this a “trick” because smaller fried fish, such as carp, are usually so low-loaded that they already meet the planned maximums today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious diversion maneuver that alone helps the economy," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a heavy metal that is highly toxic to humans and is highly enriched throughout the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The federal government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn babies".
However, the Federal Ministry of Environment states on its homepage with regard to the current maximum values that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through the burning of coal.
German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tons of mercury per year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written information from the Federal Ministry of Environment to Greens-Bundestagsabgeordnete Annalena Baerbock.
The concentration of mercury in fish such as in the Elbe, the Rhine and the Danube was "permanently and extensively exceeded," the "mirror" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide mercury warnings in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU’s RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest EU plans at: www.quecksilber-aktion.foodwatch.de
